Classically, responses to pathogens are described by the ‘zigzag’ model of plant immunity. In this model, the first level of defense is initiated upon perception of pathogen- or microbe-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs and MAMPs) and host damage-associated molecular patterns (DAMPS), by an array of plant receptors (

; 

). Perception of pathogens leads to pattern-triggered immunity (PTI) responses (

), against which some pathogens subsequently evolved effector proteins, which lead to increased susceptibility. 
A
second stronger level of effector-triggered immunity (ETI) defense responses is subsequently initiated, including expression of host resistance (R)-genes, that often initiates the hypersensitive response (

). However this model of plant immunity is now being revisited by reports highlighting overlap between the PAMPs/MAMPs and effectors, as well as between the receptors perceiving and eliciting PTI and ETI, such that a simplified model was recently proposed that refers simply to extracellularly and intracellularly triggered immunity (ExTI and InTI) (

). Notably, many of the above mentioned R-genes are linked to genetic loci that, when incorporated into germplasm, sometimes confer complete resistance to an array of diseases (

). However, while R-gene resistance is quantitatively strong, it lacks durability, and with time is generally overcome by shifts in pathogen populations (

).

In contrast to this, alleles of a number of genetic loci have been correlated with more durable, albeit quantitative, adult-plant resistance (APR) against fungal pathogens in particular. One of the best characterized of these is Lr34, with evaluation of breeding lines suggesting its effectiveness has been lasting for more than 100 years (
). This same Lr3 4 has most notably been effective against cereal rusts including leaf, stem, and stripe rusts (caused by
Puccinia triticina
,
P. graminis
, and
P. striiformis
, respectively), as well as powdery mildew and to a lesser extent spot blotch, the latter two caused by
Blumeria graminis
and
Bipolaris sorokiniana ,
respectively (
;
;
). The gene responsible for Lr34 resistance was cloned and found to encode an ATP binding cassette (ABC) transporter (
), with susceptible-associated ( Lr34sus ) and resistance-associated ( Lr34res ) alleles. These alleles are differentiated by a 3-nucleotide indel, resulting in deletion of a phenylalanine from the LR34Res protein that occurs at position 546 in the LR34Sus protein, and another single nucleotide polymorphism (SNP) converting a tyrosine at LR34Res position 634 to a histidine.
identified additional polymorphisms within Lr34 : an A /T SNP in the fourth intron and a 1-nucleotide indel in the tenth exon causing a frameshift. Determination of the four Lr34 polymorphic positions in 653 wheat accessions defined four haplotypes, but only one of which was defined as the Lr34res allele, conferring the Lr34 resistance phenotype. The presence of Lr34res has been suggested to yield constitutive defense responses in the absence of pathogen (
;
), including expression of genes linked to antimicrobial activity (proteases/chitinases), as well as constitutive expression of abscisic acid (ABA) -inducible responses (
;
).

More recent studies investigated the transport characteristics of both the LR34Sus and LR34Res versions of the encoded ABC transporter proteins. Both LR34Sus and LR34Res were shown to elicit redistribution of certain membrane phospholipids, with impact on overall cellular lipid metabolism (

). However, the observed activities with respect to phospholipids were found to be true for both versions of the receptor, complicating possible interpretations with respect to associated mechanisms underlying the resistance elicited by the 
Lr34res
allele. At the same time, ABC transporters are notoriously promiscuous in substrate preferences, leaving the door open to alternatives (

). Another report, while falling short of conclusively identifying LR34Res and Lr34Sus transport substrates, demonstrated transport of a 618 Da wheat derived metabolite by LR34Sus, that was not transported by the LR34Res version of the transporter (

). Biophysical characterization suggested, albeit still to be validated, that this metabolite might fall into the category of fluorescent dioxobilin-type chlorophyll catabolites (

), consistent with 
Lr34res
being associated with a leaf-tip necrosis phenotype and senescence (

). However, lately both resistant and susceptible associated versions of the LR34 transporter were shown to mediate transport of ABA (

). The authors furthermore provide evidence supporting the possibility of differential regulation of the resistant and susceptible versions of LR 

34 
in

planta, either by post-transcriptional or post-translational mechanisms. However, the exact nature of the regulation remains to be elucidated, and the exact role of ABA in contributing to resistance remains enigmatic.

To gain further insight into the nature of potential wheat Lr34res - associated metabolites, a comparative semi-targeted metabolomics profiling strategy was implemented. Based on previous reports suggesting an association between Lr34res and constitutive defense responses (
;
), a particular focus on the defense associated polyphenolic flavonoid family of metabolites was maintained. Working from the flag leaves of
Triticum aestivum
L. ( Poaceae ) variety ‘Thatcher’ (Tc) and the near-isogenic line (NIL) of ‘Thatcher’ into which the Lr34res allele was introgressed (Tc þLr34res ; RL6058), outcomes of a comparative liquid chromatography/mass spectroscopy (LC/MS) analysis of flavonoid rich extracts are described, with an identified target structure validated by nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy and high resolution mass spectroscopy (HRMS). Additional screening of Lr34res lines in the presence and absence of pathogen, compared to Lr34sus lines, as well as the anti-fungal activity of the target and its associated metabolites, validated original outcomes and highlighted depletion of the target upon infection. Together these findings emphasize a possible role for Lr34res in mediating rust resistance by enabling higher accumulation of anti-fungal phenylproponoid metabolites.

1D 1 H NMR spectra acquired from the enriched sample indicated 19 observable protons in methanol solution (Supplementary Fig. S2A ). The 13 C spectrum gave a carbon count of 22 with the NOE-suppressed spectrum showing 2 carbon resonances with twice the area of surrounding resonances. This confirmed the molecular formula C 22 H 22 O 8 proposed from the exact mass measurement reported above. The doubling of many of the integrated intensities in the aromatic/vinyl region indicated a high degree of symmetry in the molecule. Carbon peaks at around 169 ppm (Supplementary Fig. S2B ) indicated 2 carbonyl oxygens. Carbon peaks at around 161 ppm and 150 ppm indicated 2 phenol groups, with the carbon peak at around 69 ppm indicating a methoxyl group. Analysis of the multiplicity edited HSQC spectrum, showing directly bonded H– C ( Fig. 3 ), as well as an HMBC (Supplemental Fig. S3 ) providing correlations between carbons and protons that were separated by two, three, and sometimes in conjugated systems, four bonds were used for spin systems assignment. The HSQC showed 15 protonated carbons including 1 x CH 3 , 2 x CH 2 and the rest CH . The chemical shift of the two equivalent CH 2 groups and the CH at 4.28 and 4.15 ppm are typical for a sn-1,3 di-ester-substituted glycerol. This was confirmed from the HMBC correlations from 4.28 ppm to 169 ppm. HMBC correlations from the carbonyl carbon into the vinyl protons and then from vinyl carbons into the aromatic systems supported a dicinnamate type of substituted glycerol. The C 2 spin systems in the aromatic region supported a p -coumaroyl group on the glycerol. This was further supported by the HMBC correlations in the aromatic region. The correlation between the methyl protons at 3.87 ppm and the aromatic carbon at 114 ppm identified one of the groups as a feruloyl group. A final assignment of carbon resonances, as well as a list of related proton resonances was compiled ( Table 2 ) and presented on the proposed structure ( Fig. 3 ). This assignment agreed well with 13 C data previously reported for similar diglyceride metabolites characterized by NMR (
;
). The overall proposed structure was that of 1- O-p -coumaroyl-3- O -feruloylglycerol ( CFG ), a phenylpropanoid diglyceride reported in other plant extracts (
;
;
;
).

Despite its effective use in breeding for over 100 years (

), as well as its cloning (

) and the recent biochemical characterization of its encoded ABC transporter (

; 

; 

), the mechanism by which 
Lr34res
elicits its durable quantitative rust resistance remains to be fully understood. 
A
clearer picture of its molecular mechanism of action will allow more rational implementation of its use in breeding programs, most notably when it comes to stacking sources of resistance to enable the development of more durable qualitative resistance as fungal pathogens continue to change and adapt.

To understand the effect of Lr34res on plant metabolism, a semi-targeted metabolite profiling study was undertaken, based on a comparison of the (poly)phenolic/flavonoid families of metabolites in two NILs of wheat, Tc and Tc þLr34res . This area of specialized metabolism was targeted based on documented roles for many of these types of compounds in plant defense responses against various external stresses, including fungal pathogens (reviewed in
;
;
). Interestingly, in the absence of pathogens, these NILs had virtually identical polyphenolic/flavonoid profiles, with the exception of the observed higher accumulation of the phenylpropanoid diglyceride, CFG , in the Lr34res line ( Fig. 1 ).

Phenylpropanoid diglycerides were first identified in what is considered to be a wild relative of cultivated wheat, 

Aegilops ovata
(
Cooper et al., 1978
)

. 
CFG
in particular has been characterized across an array of other plants including, 

Tillandsia streptocarpa

, a South American herbaceous epiphyte with established natural anti-inflammatory activity (

), 

Ananas comosus

a popular tropical fruit (

) and 

Sparganium stoloniferum

, widely distributed in 
China
with anti-tumor activities (

). Phenylpropanoid diglycerides have been further identified in extracts from propolis, a product made by bees from plant exudates used in hive building, with documented antibacterial properties as well as putative antitumoral, antioxidative and immunomodulatory activities (reviewed in 

). The bioactivity of phenylpropanoid diglycerides has been patented (

) and some aspects of their biosynthesis elucidated (

). Interestingly, their overall structure is reminiscent of another well documented anti-microbial/anti-tumoral metabolite, curcumin (

). Thus, 
Lr34res
-associated increases in the accumulation of 
CFG
is entirely consistent with 
Lr34res
-associated resistance against multiple microbial pathogens (

; 

; 

).

